industry: Public administration, defence, education, human health and social work activities
comments_overall: Many of the suggestions sound like good ideas at first blush but are very complex. For example, I work with retrofitting old buildings for new use and the new energy efficiency requirements are so stringent it becomes almost impossible to do so. We need to stop expecting that we can all live in a building that will be a precise temperature regardless of the exterior temperature year-round. We cannot construct new buildings and solve this problem as that drives greater waste and use of water, their own drivers of climate change. There were others related to agriculture that had similar complexity - sound good on paper, but won't necessarily solve the problem and may cause other issues of their own. I'm very in favor of combatting climate change, but we need to be thoughtful and not just have knee-jerk or feel-good "solutions." (Public transit > electric vehicles is another one)

comments_overall: When deciding what policies to support I also weighed the potential push back from citizens. A policy might have environmental benefits, but if most people hate the policy enforcing it could lead to resistance to all carbon reducing policies. For example, banning carbon intensive food production would have a positive environmental benefit, but people would react extremely negatively to no being able to buy beef anymore. This could result in an anti-environmental backlash that would endanger future policies.

comments_overall: The questions were easy to understand. What is not easy to understand is why virtually every recommended solution impacts the wallets of consumers. It appeared that more than half of the recommendations would require higher taxes. That certainly causes no sacrifice for businesses or the government, only consumers. I saw now proposed policies or taxes that required proof those solutions would materially affect the rate of or severity of climate change. The way our doomsayer scientists are claiming climate change will kill our planet, it hardly makes sense for people to be required to pay taxes for solutions that could not possibly have an effect until after the planet has died. Look what happened in California. The state is overproducing solar energy so the electric companies have stopped paying consumers to produce any excess because the energy companies have no way to store or use it. With an alleged national electric grid (minus Texas of course), one would think California's excess solar energy could be redirected to other states with shortages or excessively high prices. How about a policy that requires the government to fund all of the climate change initiatives and research but only if it can reduce a like amount of government spending in other areas.
